06281nam a2200877Ia 9783111323756DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232024gw     fo  d z      ger d  a2023945297  a97831113237567 a10.1515/97831113237562doi  a(DE-B1597)658689  a(OCoLC)1409685877  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 ager  agwcDE 4aP130.5b.D58 2023 7aLAN0090102bisacsh04a306.44223/eng/2024020100aDiversity in Contact /chrsg. von Nataliya Levkovych. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (X, 530 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aKoloniale und Postkoloniale Linguistik / Colonial and Postcolonial Linguistics (KPL/CPL) ,x2747-4089 ;v2100tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tPart I -- tDifferential impact of colonial languages on written languages -- tContact in World Englishes at the nexus of language and culture -- tFar beyond the Caucasus -- tScenarios of Basque Language Contact -- tThe relevance of origin -- tOn the morphosyntax of place names vs. common nouns in pidgins and creoles -- tPlaces, manners, and the areal phonology of Europe -- tTravellers in time and space -- tPart II -- tThe city as multilingual utopia -- tFluid registers and fixed language concepts in postcolonial spaces -- tProlegomena to a study of code-switching in Togo and its metapragmatic functions -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Languages, Language Families, and Linguistic Areas -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributions in the edited volume deal with different aspects of language contact which were hitherto not or not sufficiently considered in linguistic research. The impact of the colonial languages Polish and German on the structures of the written varieties of Latvian is surveyed and compared. The opposite case – the impact of indigenous languages of Nigeria and Ghana on the colonial language English – is scrutinized from the perspective of the nexus of language and culture. Language contact in a diasporic context is examined in the case study on Jordanian Chechen. The effects of language contact on the lexicon and grammar of Basque are analyzed. In the in-depth study on Maltese adpositions, the influence of the contact language Italian is a central theme. The morphosyntax of place names is analyzed for the contact languages which typically arise in colonial contexts – Pidgins and Creoles. In the typological study dealing with areal phonology, languages of Europe are investigated revealing that the role of language contact is crucial for the distribution of phonological phenomena. The novel nature and new strands of research in the contributions call for further investigations and form a new component in language-contact theory.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aLanguages in contact. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Historical & Comparative.2bisacsh  aBorrowings.  aContact-induced Language Change.  aLanguage Contact.1 aAl Sheshani, Ala, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloom, Jascha de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallies, Marcus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Magnus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForker, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaase, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHober, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJäger, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevkovych, Nataliya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id